\begin_layout Section
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following two articles described in this Chapter and 
\begin_inset Flex CT - auto cross-reference
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand labelonly
reference "chap:AgRad50"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 focus on the phenomenon of mismetallation of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rad}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 zinc hook domain by other than Zn(II), potentially toxic metal ions: Hg(II)
 and Ag(I) (the later described in 
\begin_inset Flex CT - auto cross-reference
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand labelonly
reference "chap:AgRad50"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 It is a well-known fact that mercury contamination affects both ecosystem
 and human health.
 Mercury pollution stems from both sources – natural and anthropogenic,
 where after its release into the environment mercury undergoes various
 (physical and chemical, often redox-related changes).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Driscoll2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Mercury poisoning results as a consequence of exposure to mercury, the
 severity of the poisoning, as usual, is dependent on the dose and the length
 of the exposure.
 Another factor that impacts the poisoning severity is the form of the mercury
 – various mercury forms are characterized by diverse absorbability and
 reactivity towards biological targets, e.g.
 methylmercury cation 
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Methylmercury cation is a major source of mercury poisoning in human 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bernhoft2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is easily absorbed into the brain, liver, kidneys, etc., while Hg(II) for
 various reasons, including the reactions with sulfhydryl groups on erythrocytes
 or glutathione in the plasma does not easily cross the blood-brain barrier
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bernhoft2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The mercury accumulation mostly in mitochondria and in the nucleus was
 already proven years ago 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bucio1998,Christensen1988,Yoneyama1985,Konigsberg2001"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Inside the cell, organic mercury may be demethylated into inorganic mercury
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Suda1992"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
tutaj brakuje jakiegoś zdania łaczącego
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It was proven that the Hg(II) ions (a product of demethylation) may inhibit
 the activity of transcription factors that contain zinc fingers, however,
 the exact mechanism of how Hg(II) disturbs the function of the transcription
 factors is not known, as no data how mercury is coordinated by those transcript
ion factors were provided 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rodgers2001"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 One of the mechanisms of the inhibition of the transcription factors could
 be the formation of the aberrant metal binding site, as Hg(II) in the aqueous
 environment tends to form linear complexes, however, the formation of complexes
 with higher coordination number is possible, those complexes usually are
 distorted, with T-shaped geometry of the complex being an extreme example
 of the three-coordinated species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chakraborty2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In  living organisms, correspondingly to the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{hsab}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, Hg(II), as a soft Lewis acid will preferentially react with sulfhydryl
 groups (soft Lewis bases), therefore it is not surprising that the cell
 detoxifying mechanisms copiously utilize thiolates to sense (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{merr}
\end_layout

\end_inset

), sequester (e.g.
 metallothioneins), and to enzymatically process mercury compounds to less
 toxic forms or to Hg(0) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ledwidge2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Marginal
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hg(0) is the major form of mercury emitted to the atmosphere.
 Hg(II) buried in sediments may be reduced to Hg(0), which can be re-emited
 to the astmosphere 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Christakis2021"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the cytoplasm Hg(II) will preferentially form diagonal complexes with
 low molecular weight compounds with thiol groups (i.e.
 cysteine, glutathione), however, when Hg(II) interacts with the protein,
 like in the case of Hg(II)-substituted rubredoxin, the protein may already
 impose a structurally defined metal binding site, where the Hg(II) will
 adopt a tetrahedral or pseudotetrahedral architecture 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Faller2000"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The observed coordination in the crystal structure does not necessarily
 correspond to the Hg(II) binding site formed in the solution, as has been
 verified in the case of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{atox}
\end_layout

\end_inset

—contrarily to the crystal structure (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "1FE4"
target "https://www.rcsb.org/structure/1FE4"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, dimer, crystallized at pH 6.5) in solution (pH 7.5) Hg(II) prefers to form
 linear complexes with monomeric protein 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "uczkowski2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

